    "eyebrow": "Primary Source Analysis",
    "num": "04",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">04</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Primary Source Analysis</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Examining Early Definitions of 'Texican'</h2><ul><li>Primary documents from 1820s use 'Texican' to describe Mexican settlers</li><li>Terms reflect self-identification and external labeling</li><li>Language and context reveal cultural and political nuances</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Primary sources from the period show how 'Texican' was used by both settlers and officials. These documents help us understand how identity was constructed and perceived in Mexican Texas. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> An 1825 land grant document refers to the recipient as a 'Texican citizen,' emphasizing Mexican legal status.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Analyze a primary source excerpt and identify how 'Texican' is used to convey identity.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Ignoring the context of primary sources and reading terms with modern assumptions.</p></div></div>",
