      "h": "Cultural Continuity and Adaptation Among Texicans",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Texicans inherited a rich cultural heritage from Spanish colonial times, which evolved under Mexican governance. Their identity included language, religion, and customs distinct from Anglo settlers.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from everything-everywhere.com; tshaonline.org. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Texicans descended from Spanish colonial settlers and Mexican citizens</li><li>Maintained Catholic faith and Spanish language</li><li>Blended indigenous, Spanish, and Mexican cultural elements</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>A Texican family celebrating Catholic feast days in San Antonio reflects this cultural continuity.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Identify cultural traits that distinguished Texicans from Anglo settlers.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming all early Texas settlers shared the same cultural practices.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> everything-everywhere.com; tshaonline.org <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup></p>"
