      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Texicans relied heavily on cattle ranching, which shaped their social and economic structures. Trade networks connected them to indigenous peoples and Mexican markets.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from everything-everywhere.com; tshaonline.org. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Ranching was a primary economic activity</li><li>Trade with Native tribes and other Mexican provinces</li><li>Agriculture supplemented ranching economies</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>A Texican rancher trading cattle hides with Native American tribes for goods.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Discuss how ranching influenced Texican social organization.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Overlooking the importance of trade and agriculture alongside ranching.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> everything-everywhere.com; tshaonline.org <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup></p>"
