      "h": "Texican Political Identity and Challenges",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Texicans were Mexican citizens who engaged in local governance but experienced growing tensions as Anglo immigration increased and political dynamics shifted.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from everything-everywhere.com; lauriemooremoore.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Loyal to Mexican government but with local autonomy</li><li>Participated in provincial politics of Coahuila y Texas</li><li>Faced tensions with Anglo settlers and central authorities</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Texican leaders serving in local councils balancing Mexican laws and frontier realities.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Analyze how Texicans navigated loyalty to Mexico amid changing political pressures.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming Texicans uniformly opposed Anglo settlers or Mexican authorities.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> everything-everywhere.com; lauriemooremoore.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p>"
