      "h": "Synthesizing Texican Identity Concepts",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> This checkpoint reinforces key concepts about who Texicans were, their cultural background, and how their identity terms shifted historically.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from everything-everywhere.com; lauriemooremoore.com; tshaonline.org. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Texicans were Hispanic settlers of Mexican Texas before 1836</li><li>They maintained Spanish-Mexican cultural traditions</li><li>Identity terms evolved with political changes in Texas</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Recall the distinctions between Texican, Texian, and Texan identities discussed earlier.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Explain in your own words what makes a Texican distinct from a Texian or Texan.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Overgeneralizing or confusing identity terms across time periods.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> everything-everywhere.com; lauriemooremoore.com; tshaonline.org <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup></p>"
