      "h": "Deep Dive: Political Loyalties in a Contested Borderland",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> During the early 19th century, Texicans navigated the conflict between Mexico and Spain, sometimes supporting Mexican independence while also protecting local autonomy, reflecting complex political loyalties.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; lauriemooremoore.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Texicans were caught in the struggle between Mexico and Spain over Texas</li><li>They often had divided loyalties influenced by local interests</li><li>Their actions impacted territorial control and political developments</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Some Texicans supported Mexican revolutionary forces against Spain, while others prioritized local defense against external threats.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Evaluate how Texican loyalties might shift based on political and economic pressures.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming Texicans uniformly supported one side oversimplifies their strategic choices.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; lauriemooremoore.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p>"
