      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Role-play helps learners embody Texican perspectives, exploring the nuanced cultural and political factors influencing their decisions during the Texas Revolution.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; lauriemooremoore.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Learners will simulate Texican viewpoints during the revolution</li><li>Focus on cultural tensions, political loyalties, and personal stakes</li><li>Prepare arguments reflecting diverse Texican experiences</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>A learner might argue from the perspective of a Texican loyal to Mexico concerned about Anglo dominance and cultural loss.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Develop a position statement representing a Texican viewpoint on independence or loyalty to Mexico.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Oversimplifying Texican positions into pro- or anti-independence without cultural context.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; lauriemooremoore.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p>"
