      "h": "Deep Dive: Using Role-Play to Explore Historical Complexity",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> This interactive role-play allows learners to actively debate Texican loyalties, deepening understanding of the cultural and political complexities during the Texas Revolution.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; lauriemooremoore.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Engage in a debate representing different Texican positions</li><li>Explore cultural tensions between Mexican loyalty and Texan independence</li><li>Reflect on how identity influenced political choices</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>One learner argues for maintaining Mexican ties to preserve culture; another advocates for independence to protect local autonomy.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Participate in the debate, using historical evidence to support your Texican position.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Allowing the debate to become polarized without acknowledging nuanced middle positions.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; lauriemooremoore.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p>"
