    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">25</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Primary Sources</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Exploring Texican Letters and Correspondence</h2><ul><li>Letters reveal personal experiences and social networks of Texicans</li><li>Provide insights into daily life, political views, and cultural identity</li><li>Often written in Spanish, reflecting linguistic heritage</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Analyzing letters from Texican archives helps us understand their perspectives on settlement, family, and political events. These documents are primary sources that capture authentic voices from the period. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A letter from a Texican settler to a family member discusses land disputes and relations with neighboring Native tribes.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Examine a provided letter excerpt and identify key themes about Texican life and challenges.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Avoid assuming letters represent all Texicans uniformly; consider author background and context.</p></div></div>",
