    "num": "35",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">35</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Transfer</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Applying Source Analysis to Other Historical Contexts</h2><ul><li>Use skills learned to analyze primary sources from different regions or periods</li><li>Recognize universal challenges in interpreting historical documents</li><li>Adapt critical methods to diverse cultural and political settings</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">The analytical techniques developed for Texican sources are broadly applicable to historical research in other contexts. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Comparing analysis of Texican letters with letters from early American settlers to identify common interpretive strategies.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Select a primary source from another historical context and apply the evaluation framework learned.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming methods apply identically without considering contextual differences.</p></div></div>",
