      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> The analytical techniques developed for Texican sources are broadly applicable to historical research in other contexts.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from libguides.tamusa.edu; texasstudies.org. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Use skills learned to analyze primary sources from different regions or periods</li><li>Recognize universal challenges in interpreting historical documents</li><li>Adapt critical methods to diverse cultural and political settings</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Comparing analysis of Texican letters with letters from early American settlers to identify common interpretive strategies.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Select a primary source from another historical context and apply the evaluation framework learned.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming methods apply identically without considering contextual differences.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> libguides.tamusa.edu; texasstudies.org <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup></p>"
