    "num": "37",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">37</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Etymology and Identity</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">The Origin of 'Texas': From Caddo 'táysha' to Texican Identity</h2><ul><li>'Texas' derives from the Caddo word 'táysha' meaning 'friend' or 'ally'.</li><li>This indigenous term was adopted by Spanish explorers and settlers.</li><li>The name reflects early intercultural relationships shaping regional identity.</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">The name 'Texas' originates from the Caddo word 'táysha', signifying friendship. Spanish colonists adopted this term, which became central to the identity of the region and its inhabitants, including the Texicans. This etymology highlights indigenous influence often overlooked in Texican history (s6, s8). <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Spanish explorers used 'Tejas' to refer to friendly Caddo tribes, which evolved into the name of the province and later the state.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Consider how the adoption of indigenous terms can influence settler identities. How might this shape the Texican sense of belonging?</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming 'Texas' is purely a Spanish or Anglo invention without indigenous roots.</p></div></div>",
    "paper": {
      "secnum": "Deep Dive 37",
      "h": "Indigenous Linguistic Influence on Texican Identity",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> The name 'Texas' originates from the Caddo word 'táysha', signifying friendship. Spanish colonists adopted this term, which became central to the identity of the region and its inhabitants, including the Texicans. This etymology highlights indigenous influence often overlooked in Texican history (s6, s8).</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from everything-everywhere.com; tshaonline.org. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>'Texas' derives from the Caddo word 'táysha' meaning 'friend' or 'ally'.</li><li>This indigenous term was adopted by Spanish explorers and settlers.</li><li>The name reflects early intercultural relationships shaping regional identity.</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Spanish explorers used 'Tejas' to refer to friendly Caddo tribes, which evolved into the name of the province and later the state.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Consider how the adoption of indigenous terms can influence settler identities. How might this shape the Texican sense of belonging?</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming 'Texas' is purely a Spanish or Anglo invention without indigenous roots.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> everything-everywhere.com; tshaonline.org <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup></p>"
    },
