    "id": "slide50",
    "eyebrow": "Indigenous Influence",
    "num": "38",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">38</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Indigenous Influence</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">The Significance of Indigenous Contributions to Texican Identity</h2><ul><li>Indigenous peoples influenced Texican culture beyond language.</li><li>Trade, alliances, and intermarriage shaped social and political life.</li><li>Recognizing indigenous roles corrects historical oversights.</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texican identity was not formed in isolation but through ongoing interactions with indigenous groups. These relationships influenced cultural practices, social structures, and political alliances, underscoring the importance of indigenous contributions to Texican history (s6, s8). <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Texicans often engaged in trade and military alliances with neighboring Native American tribes, which affected settlement security and cultural exchange.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Identify examples of indigenous influence on Texican daily life or governance.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Ignoring indigenous agency and viewing Texicans as solely European-descended settlers.</p></div></div>",
