      "secnum": "Deep Dive 38",
      "h": "Beyond Language: Indigenous Roles in Texican Society",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Texican identity was not formed in isolation but through ongoing interactions with indigenous groups. These relationships influenced cultural practices, social structures, and political alliances, underscoring the importance of indigenous contributions to Texican history (s6, s8).</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from everything-everywhere.com; tshaonline.org. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Indigenous peoples influenced Texican culture beyond language.</li><li>Trade, alliances, and intermarriage shaped social and political life.</li><li>Recognizing indigenous roles corrects historical oversights.</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Texicans often engaged in trade and military alliances with neighboring Native American tribes, which affected settlement security and cultural exchange.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Identify examples of indigenous influence on Texican daily life or governance.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Ignoring indigenous agency and viewing Texicans as solely European-descended settlers.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> everything-everywhere.com; tshaonline.org <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup></p>"
