    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">46</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Final Review</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Key Takeaways on Texican Identity and Indigenous Influence</h2><ul><li>Texican identity is rooted in indigenous, Spanish, and Mexican cultural intersections.</li><li>The name 'Texas' reflects indigenous origins and early alliances.</li><li>Recognizing indigenous contributions is essential for accurate historical understanding.</li><li>Texican identity exemplifies frontier cultural hybridity.</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">This slide summarizes the essential points about Texican identity and the critical role of indigenous influence, preparing learners for final assessment and application (s2, s6, s7, s8, s10). <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> The term 'Texican' encapsulates a complex identity shaped by multiple cultural and historical forces.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Reflect on how this understanding changes your perspective on Texas history.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Overlooking the complexity and multicultural nature of Texican identity.</p></div></div>",
